I've been struggling with severe anxiety and depression for quite some time now. Other than walking to class, I was never really that active. I don't care for sports and don't need to lose weight with intense workouts. The past few months I've been working on doing yoga consistently, and this year is the most I've exercised regularly, missing a few days per week. I was only doing beginners' yoga videos for a while, but now I feel strong enough to do the monthly yoga challenges even if some of the poses are hard to get through. This is the first one I'm doing. I'm proud of myself even though I still struggle with sleeping too much and not being able to concentrate on things I need to get done. I love refreshing the page after every practice and seeing how many people were doing it with me - today it was a little over 200. Yoga is perfect for helping me feel calmer and getting in shape at the same time, so I hope I can keep it up.

I can‚Äôt overstate how helpful this video was to my mental well-being. I‚Äôve attempted a couple of 30 day courses before but always fell off for one reason or another. I decided this time I was going to stick to it no matter what, even if I took a day or two off I‚Äôd come back it. During this particular video, while doing the breathing exercise I had this moment where I thought to myself ‚Äúis this helpful for me? Maybe I should just stretch instead..‚Äù but I continued with the breathing and transitioned into the meditation. As we were going into the lying down portion it dawned on me that even though I felt like I wanted to do something else while we were doing the breathing exercises, it was preparing me to put my mind and body at rest to meditate. That thought process transitioned into several thoughts after the practice that made some profound revelations about what I‚Äôm doing professionally and personally in my life and that even though I may not enjoy exactly what is happening right now, I should embrace it as I‚Äôm being prepared for what‚Äôs next. I‚Äôve never felt more connected with myself or to my yoga practice than I have after this video. Your affirmations and warmness are so appreciated. I can‚Äôt wait for tonight so I can dive into day 9 but I see my self coming back to this particular video on a regular basis. Keep up the amazing work and thank you

Im relieved to see that so many others also felt emotional during today's meditation. For some reason, so many childhood memories flooded through my head, including ones I didn't even realize I had. It saddened me. With so many new changes occuring in my adult life, I became upset knowing that I would never experience those memories again and that life will now be filled with so many responsibilities and decisions. I'm not sure where all these emotions came from, and it's amazing how they can come through when meditating. Although I'm still feeling a bit of sadness, I do feel some reassurance that with my ever-changing life, comes new memories and new adventures to embark on. Thank you Adrian for providing a safe place where I can sit and ponder about the past, present and future. Deep down I know it's a beautiful thing.

Here's my day eight check-in... I think I've forgotten to comment the past few days, but I'm glad to still be here to take part with Move. Today was a harder day for me, because I struggle with being still and able to hear my own thoughts. I had a harder time staying present because of these negative thought spirals I always find myself stuck in. I don't know why I'm so critical of myself, it just feels like something that can't be helped... But I'm sick of staying where I am out of futility. I'm going to learn to value my own opinion this year, my own feelings, my personality - I don't want to have to be told who I am by others anymore. I need to become someone strong and self-sustaining. I don't want to get knocked down every time someone hurts me. I don't want to spend my time waiting around for someone else's validation before I can start living. I need to live for myself. I know in my heart that I'm a good person, and I should be able trust my decisions without needing approval for them. I don't want to waste any more days waiting on the words of someone who is incapable of caring about me.
Thank you for this opportunity to take this journey with you Adriene, I'm so happy to be here on day eight!

I enjoyed and struggled some with this practice. I have Tourette‚Äôs syndrome which causes mostly motor tics in my shoulders neck and legs. I‚Äôve always struggled with stillness. When the doctor says hold still I find it to hard and notice all the tic sensations in my body with it usually increasing as I hold still. This happened to me in a way today as we laid on our backs and tried to soften however I let myself soften and let the tics that came happen rather than tightening to hold them back. I realized I must spend an enormous amount of time surpassing by holding and tightening through the day. This was such an eye opener for me to see my softness might look different and towards the end the tics were less intense and fewer. I never thought to use yoga for my Tourette‚Äôs but will now. Meditation is also so hard as I have adhd and thought tics (intrusive repetitive thoughts). Today I finally feel like I could do these types of practice and not be doing it ‚Äòwrong‚Äô because I tic. I feel like I‚Äôm holding my tics back less today although they are happening more. Perhaps this is the direction I need. 10 years of holding things in can wear one down.

Every year I look forward to rest day, it's one of my favorite practices. But today when I woke up I got some really bad news and I was just feeling so anxious and irritable. I tried to keep calm during the practice, but it wasn't until we laid down and Adriene said "let the mental chatter rest" that I could actually let go and just be in my body and let my mind stop fixating on trying to escape my feelings. I was appreciating it so much that it was quite difficult to move to the fetal position, but eventually I moved there too because I really like practicing together with the community and being united in our actions, and I realized that I was just adding to my struggles because by trying to escape my painful emotions I was ignoring my inner child. And moving to the fetal position reminded me that I have a vulnerable side that was really hurt by being ignored by me. So I took some time to just listen to that part of me. What a good practice. This practice showed another part I can improve on besides physical strength, and that is flexibility. Bringing the head to the knees is simply not possible, I‚Äôm at roughly 90 degrees here. I‚Äôm also noticing that I still haven‚Äôt recovered from impingement syndrome in my left shoulder, when doing cactus me left arm definitely doesn‚Äôt want to go down to the ground fully üòÇ.
But if I‚Äôve learned anything from these practices with Adriene, I don‚Äôt pressure or rush any of the exercises. I try to ease my way into them with very delicate movements and only light and gentle pushes, especially when it comes to flexibility exercises. The only way to get better at this is by staying consistent and hopefully get better ever so slightly with each new exercise.

I had an incredible moment while laying down in shavasana. It is hard to describe and I am still trying to process it but I felt like I need to share it down here in the comments, maybe it will mean something to one of you. Maybe it'll be meaningful for me only, but it is still enough reasons for me to share it. I do have a habit of meditation and I believe I have improved my skills of experiencing the moment and staying there while meditating over the years. But today I felt, actually _lived_ something I never have before. While allowing myself to relax with Adriane's guide I came to realize I only exist in this moment. For that second absolutely noting mattered. There was no future and no past, just the moment. I did't even think about being in the moment. Just nothing went through my mind. A complete nothingness. All though it might sound scary it was actually very pleasant to be in that state. It was a like a moment of dissociation, but not in a bad way. More like a climax maybe. It felt like I achieved the consciousness of the nothingness. Like I said it is really hard to describe in words because  I wasn't really _I_, I was just _there_ without being anything. As I allowed myself to be in this situation this tingling sensation ran over my scalp down to my spine, so strong I felt my body shake for a bit. And just at the exact same time, simultaneously with that shake, the items in my room (I have some paint bottles and some glass bottles standing on my bookshelf) next to where I was lying down made a sound. As if there was a tiny earthquake and they hit each other briefly. That sound kinda brought me back to myself because I had an immediate fear response. I almost opened my eyes to check what was going on with the bottles but I resisted the tendency to do so. I just took a deep breath and allowed myself to let that fear go. I am a strong defender of empirical science so I tend to be skeptical about "scientifically hard to explain" spiritual events. But experiencing this on the first hand, I do believe that  there are mystical things about us and this world that are yet beyond our comprehension. Does feel odd for me to write this down but I kinda believe that what moved those bottles was the tingling response in my body. That sensation was maybe like a wave started in my body but didn't stop there, instead it kept on going beyond my physical body and affected the items in the room. It may have gone further even, but I don't know. I even think it may not have started in _my body_ but in someone else's and it reached to me. That is why I wanted to write this down here. Because right now I feel deeply connected to you, some people I probably will never get to see, hear, touch, know. But I may have just received your sensation. And I want to thank you for sharing it with me.

I used to think that grabbing a blanket, or a pillow, or putting on a pair of fuzzy socks, was a waste of my time. "Why?" I thought to myself.. "It's not like those things are going to make THAT much difference." Well, an adrenal fatigue, burnout, and an episode of exhaustion-related psychosis later, let me tell you this much: those things make ALL the difference. Slowing down, and tending to ourselves in that way, teaches us our self-worth, it rekindles us with our True Self. It is a matter of beautifying all the in-betweens, and taking the time to make every moment, every breath: SPECIAL. It is self-Love, it is self-Care, it is self-Respect. Taking the time to do those little things, transfers into my daily life, and it teaches me healthier boundaries, better relationship with my body and my feminine cycles. Please, if you are new here, DO take that time to give yourself all the "extras," for your life outside of the mat, will be that much more rewarding.
